sentence: D ividend payers with strong growth can be the best of both worlds, providing them income and appreciation potential.
Here's a quick look at five stocks with double-digit profit growth and dividend yields of 2% or better.
Tech consulting giantAccenture ( ACN ) has a five-year average earnings growth rate of 13% on five-year revenue growth of 8%.
Its shares are finding support at the 10-week moving average and holding near an all-time high.
Accenture is scheduled to report fiscal third-quarter results on June 25 before the open.
Analysts expect a slight decline in earnings, which would be Accenture's first quarterly earnings decline in more than two years.
Revenue is seen slipping 3% to $7.55 billion.
Wells Fargo ( WFC ) is trading in buy range from a May breakout past 56.39.
The San Francisco-based bank touched a record high last week and sports a five-year profit growth rate of 16%.
In April, Wells Fargo raised its quarterly dividend by 2.5 cents to 37.5 cents a share.
The stock currently yields about 2.5% on an annualized basis.
Home improvement retailerHome Depot ( HD ) reported May 19 that fiscal Q1 earnings climbed 21%.
That's roughly in line with the chain's five-year annualized growth of 23%.
Home Depot is finding resistance at its 10-week line as the stock tries to base.
It will pay a 59-cent dividend on June 18 to holders of record on June 4.
Dr Pepper Snapple Group ( DPS ) has pulled back to a test of support at its 200-day moving average after a lengthy uptrend.
The stock is building a potential flat base.
The beverage giant's five-year earnings track record shows 12% annualized growth.
A 48-cent dividend is payable July 7 to holders of record as of June 15.
IBM ( IBM ) has the highest annual yield of the group at 3.1%, but its shares are troubled, trading below a declining 200-day line.
And forward estimates are weak.
